    <para id="id11997503">V. EFFECTS OF SAMPLING ABOVE, AT, AND BELOW THE NYQUIST RATE</para>
    <para id="id11934126">1/ Effect of varying the sampling rate</para>
    <figure id="id11934136">
      <media id="id1171586603360" alt=""><image src="../../media/graphics16-21bd.png" mime-type="image/png" height="234" width="401"/></media>
    </figure>
    <para id="id11941680">2/ Aliasing and truncation</para>
    <figure id="id11941687">
      <media id="id1171586603405" alt=""><image src="../../media/graphics17-7046.png" mime-type="image/png" height="253" width="234"/></media>
    </figure>
    <para id="id10025146">In general, if x(t) is sampled below the Nyquist rate</para>
    <para id="id11544132"><m:math>

 <m:mrow>

  <m:mfrac>

   <m:mn>1</m:mn>

   <m:mi>T</m:mi>

  </m:mfrac>

